I have a bad story about my brother who went skiing and the people from the ambulance and even the doctors thought he was faking it. We went skiing and he missed a turn an ran into a tree. He was skiing little bit more but felt big pain in his Belly. He got sick and pale and had to vomit so we called an ambulance. It took them one hour to arrive and nearly 2 and a half!!!! hour to arrive at the hospital (because of traffic(I was there before them)). They told him he has to wait for sure more then an hour because there are a lot of emergency cases today. He waited patiently even under big pain. He was laying and I noticed his belly looked a little "pregnant" like very filled. I told the doctors roaming around and they brought him to an room. The doctor was sitting on his computer (not caring about him at all) telling us that he has to wait for his documents arriving from the counter. At this moment my brother looked nearly dead to me ( very pale and a stare face so I was very worried). Finally they checked him and the saw that his spleen was burst open and he had more than 3 liters of blood already in his belly (that is why he looked so "pregnant"). Immediately 3 doctors rushed to him and gave him (all in all) 7 bloodtransfusions and the told us he had to get his spleen removed. All in all did they set him up for the surgery 8 times but changed there mind always in last minute (because it is very bad for your immune system to loose your spleen). All in all he stayed 2 Weeks in Hospital and gladly had no surgery just lots of lots of painkillers and other infusions and stuff. I just want to say that he is 12!!! years old and a very tough guy. He didn't scream or something and was very patient even EVERYBODY saw his pain and his full belly expect the nurses...
I am so glad they didn't operate him but how they treated him at the beginning was very heartbreaking to see that at the beginning (they were extremely kind after that). So Please never say you know someone is faking something (even if you are not a doctor) you never know their true story.

Doctors and other medical professionals have the ability to help just as much as they have to ability to hurt. I get that they see a lot of people drug-seeking and being difficult. But that should never, ever carry over to the next patient.

I’ve had two ER visits relevant to this, one where I wasn’t believed, one where I was.
The one where I wasn’t believed, happened after a strenuous workout. I was in horrible pain, I thought I’d broken something. My dad took me to the ER, and while a nurse did an X-ray, (while rolling her eyes), I was never even seen by a doctor. After a few hours, I was told I was being discharged. I asked what was wrong with me, and a nurse said she didn’t know, and gave me a sheet of paper that had these standard things you should do after such and such happened, (including a tetanus shot), which wasn’t helpful at all. I saw my primary care physician the next day, who figured out that the problem was I’d applied heat (after my workout) to an inflamed area, causing the severe pain. I believe strongly that I was treated the way I was because I was wearing ratty clothes and old shoes, my exercise clothes.
My other ER visit, same hospital, where I was believed, I had chest pain and a rapid heart rate. I thought I was having a heart attack. I was admitted, seen by a doctor, who figured out after asking me and my father, (who again drove me), some questions that I was having a panic attack. He was very nice and I appreciated that he understood I wasn’t “faking.” I truly thought I was dying.

I'm 29 years old, and had to go to the ER for chest pain and tachycardia (really fast heartbeat). The staff didn't hesitate to get me into a room. It didn't help that I was out of breath and walking very slowly and deliberately to avoid getting dizzy.


In spite of my age, they took me seriously, did all the tests to try and find out what was going on, and eventually were only able to determine that it wasn't a heart attack, or something equally serious.


So yeah, even if it turns out to be nothing serious, take the patient seriously until you have irrefutable proof of what's happening.

snippet.textDisplay:
In response to the first video, anyone can post videos, I advocate free choices and if it’s separate from how you perform your job it shouldn’t have an implication. With that said my opinion is that the lack of empathy required to view it that way is troubling. Often the people looking for attention, need the most help. Perhaps they are lonely or scared and anxious being away from home and just need a reason to have attention. I doubt many if anyone thinks “I just feel like being a pest and I’ll make up a situation to do that”

Doctors are not psychologists and are not there to treat those situations outside of a physical aliment. However they need to be compassionate and aware of them.

As for the second video, again it’s a bit of a lack of critical thinking to post that as a professional, I’m sure doctors feel that way and can joke among themselves the same as many professions listening to people who don’t know, this is posted to the 99.9% of people who are the ones who are anxious and considering our most potent instinct is to survive, yes patients might be a little pushy when it comes to their survival in their eyes - as a professional you know that it’s not the case, to the person who believes they maybe in grave danger, it’s not like telling them their internet signal will be fine in a couple hours and they calm down.

The real challenge I think for doctors in general is hard, which is why so many come across so badly. On the one hand you have to be logical minded to navigate the diagnosis and on the other hand you have to understand that when dealing with people in emotional states it’s highly illogical. We are not robots though, and the world be worse if we removed those human anxieties and emotions.
